65292;&#24635;&#22312;&#26377;&#31354;&#30340;&#26102;&#20505;&#32452;&#32455;&#25105;&#21644;&#20854;&#20182;&#30340;&#26379;&#21451;&#32858;&#20250;&#65292;&#20063;&#20174;&#19981;&#22312;&#36825;&#20123;&#20107;&#24773;&#30340;&#33457;&#36153;&#19978;&#35745;&#36739;&#12290;&#30456;&#27604;&#36215;&#26469;&#65292;&#25105;&#20316;&#20026;&#20182;&#30340;&#26379;&#21451;&#23454;&#22312;&#19981;&#22815;&#22909;&#65292;&#22312;&#30123;&#24773;&#26399;&#38388;&#37117;&#27809;&#26377;&#32473;&#20104;&#20182;&#24212;&#26377;&#30340;&#25903;&#25345;&#12290;&#21518;&#26469;&#21363;&#20415;&#25105;&#31163;&#24320;&#20102;CITA&#32487;&#32493;&#25105;&#30340;&#23398;&#19994;&#65292;&#39558;&#38742;&#20063;&#27809;&#26377;&#30095;&#36828;&#25105;&#12290;&#20182;&#20174;&#26469;&#19981;&#22240;&#20026;&#33258;&#24049;&#30340;&#25104;&#32489;&#39556;&#20658;&#65292;&#20063;&#20174;&#26469;&#19981;&#22240;&#20026;&#21035;&#20154;&#24180;&#36731;&#19981;&#25026;&#20107;&#23601;&#35745;&#36739;&#12290;&#20182;&#27704;&#36828;&#26159;&#31215;&#26497;&#30340;&#65292;&#28201;&#26262;&#30340;&#65292;&#19982;&#20154;&#20026;&#21892;&#30340;&#65292;&#21253;&#23481;&#30340;&#12290;</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c7"
              >&#39558;&#38742;&#20540;&#24471;&#26356;&#38271;&#20037;&#30340;&#29983;&#21629;&#21644;&#38738;&#26149;&#12290;&#25105;&#30693;&#36947;&#22914;&#26524;&#20182;&#22914;&#26524;&#20877;&#26377;&#20960;&#21313;&#24180;&#30340;&#29983;&#21629;&#65292;&#20182;&#19968;&#23450;&#20173;&#26087;&#20250;&#26159;&#19968;&#20010;&#22909;&#26379;&#21451;&#65292;&#22909;&#21516;&#20107;&#65292;&#22909;&#22825;&#25991;&#29289;&#29702;&#23398;&#23478;&#65307;&#23545;&#20110;&#20182;&#30340;&#29238;&#27597;&#65292;&#20182;&#20250;&#26159;&#20010;&#20986;&#33394;&#30340;&#20799;&#23376;&#65307;&#22914;&#26524;&#20182;&#26377;&#20102;&#33258;&#24049;&#23478;&#24237;&#65292;&#20063;&#20250;&#26159;&#19968;&#20010;&#22909;&#29238;&#20146;&#65292;&#22909;&#19976;&#22827;&#12290;&#20182;&#20250;&#32487;&#32493;&#25317;&#26377;&#19968;&#20010;&#22914;&#27492;&#29305;&#21035;&#30340;&#28789;&#39746;&#21644;&#20805;&#23454;&#30340;&#29983;&#21629;&#12290;&#31185;&#23398;&#23478;&#26159;&#21807;&#29289;&#30340;&#65292;&#20294;&#39558;&#38742;&#36824;&#33021;&#26377;&#26469;&#19990;&#65292;&#21363;&#20415;&#36825;&#21644;&#22825;&#25991;&#29289;&#29702;&#23398;&#23478;&#30340;&#19990;&#30028;&#35266;&#26159;&#20914;&#31361;&#30340;&#12290;&#20182;&#36824;&#26377;&#24456;&#22810;&#26410;&#31455;&#30340;&#24515;&#24895;&#65292;&#20182;&#36824;&#24819;&#21435;&#28779;&#26143;&#12290;&#22914;&#26524;&#26377;&#26469;&#19990;&#65292;&#24076;&#26395;&#20182;&#25152;&#27714;&#30340;&#65292;&#19968;&#19968;&#23454;&#29616;&#12290;</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2"><span class="c7">&nbsp;</span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c7"
              >&ldquo; Jing was one of the very first few people I acquainted
              with at CITA. We quickly became friends after my first few months
              working there. He was outgoing, extrovert, generous, and kind. He
              looked carefree from the outside but was actually sensitive and
              caring inside, and always knew how to stand in other
              people&rsquo;s shoes. He was a great colleague and a loyal friend.
              He was slightly older than me and was truly an older brother to
              me. He had never been an overbearing person even though he had
              achieved so much as a researcher; he had never ever been even a
              little bit patronizing though he was older and had more
              experiences than me. He had always been optimistic, warm,
              amicable, and loving.</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c7"
              >I am not an astrophysicist and helped with the administrative
              work at CITA. Since I have a background in arts instead of
              science, I constantly struggled at work at the beginning. Jing was
              my go-to person when I had problems. He was extremely patient and
              respectful. He never sent me away even when my questions and
              concerns were nothing but burdens to him. He helped me through my
              entire working time at CITA and always got everyone together for
              dinners and parties. At all those gatherings, he was always the
              person who took care of everything and was always generous to his
              friends and colleagues. In comparison, I was such a mediocre
              friend who barely provided any support to him during the Covid!
              Even after I left CITA, Jing did not become a stranger and
              continued to be a close friend to me.</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c7"
              >He certainly deserved a longer life and youth. I know if he had a
              few more decades of life, he would continue to be a good friend, a
              good colleague, and a good astrophysicist; he would continue to be
              a remarkable son to his parents, and if he had a family of his
              own, he would be a loving father to his children and a caring
              husband to his partner. He would continue to have a fulfilling
              life and a unique soul.</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c7"
              >Science is materialist. But I wish another life for Jing, even
              though reincarnation is contradictory to the scientific belief
              hold by many beloving astrophysicists. Jing had many wishes. He
              wanted to go to the Mars. I wish he would be able to achieve all
              those wishes, one by one, in another life.&rdquo; &mdash; Jade
              Yujia Shi
            </span>
          </p>
          <p class="c2"><span class="c7">&nbsp;</span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >&ldquo;Jing was always one of those people I looked forward to
              seeing at a meeting or conference. He never had any airs about
              him, was always welcoming, positive, and kind, and was genuinely
              fun to be around. I hope that we can look to his example in our
              own lives and try to live up to that ideal. I will miss
              him.&rdquo; - Froney Crawford</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >&ldquo;Jing&rsquo;s one of the first pulsar people I met. We did
              our GBT observer training together and I&rsquo;m still curious how
              he convinced their guide to let his group take pictures standing
              on the dish. He&rsquo;s been a welcome voice of humour and insight
              on telecons, and someone I got excited to see when I heard he was
              going to a conference. Nothing can make this better but I hope
              it&rsquo;s some solace to know that other people saw he was a good
              man and miss him too. He deserved so many more years in the world,
              and the world would have been better for it.
            </span>
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >Jing and I didn&rsquo;t quite connect sometimes, but we muddled
              through with lots of laughs along the way. I remember an incident
              early on at a conference. Jing approached and asked me if it was
              true that English people put milk in their tea (from his face it
              was clear he either thought it was a strangely widespread myth or
              evidence that we are all aliens). I confirmed that we did and said
              he should try it, not realizing that to me &ldquo;tea&rdquo; meant
              black tea and to him &ldquo;tea&rdquo; meant green tea. He looked
              very skeptical and said I&rsquo;d have to show him how to do it.
              Next coffee-break he approached with a cup of tea and one of those
              tiny cups of milk, clearly expecting some secret trick to
              transform this concoction into something drinkable. He tried it,
              his face dropped, and he tried to be diplomatic before laughing
              and breaking into &ldquo;you English have very strange
              tastes!!&rdquo;. I tried it (I can confirm that milk and green tea
              do not go well together!), we realized our mistake and more
              laughter ensued. He made a tea reference at every conference for
              years afterwards.</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >One particular Jing-moment keeps going round in my head. I have a
              NASA sticker on my laptop from Jing. When he gave it to me he
              grinned and said he loved having them because everyone always
              wants one. He was so happy to have something to give to other
              people. I hope to be more like him.&rdquo; - Kathryn Crowter</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >I had the pleasure of knowing Jing for many years, at least since
              2011. What a super-smart, delightful, zany human being! Jing
              personified loving life and sharing that love with all around him.
              You just couldn&rsquo;t have a bad time if Jing was in the room.
              But, of course, he had a serious and dedicated side, too. What he
              did for pulsar timing with PINT is and will continue to be a
              gigantic contribution to the work that we do. He was wonderfully
              proud of his work, as he should have been. He loved the pulsar
              community, and he had certainly found a place for himself with the
              Toronto group. What a gigantic loss to everyone who knew him. Our
              hearts go out to his family who did not get to see him very much
              in recent years. Know that he was loved by many and that we will
              find ways of keeping his memory alive and passing on his legacy to
              others.<br />&ndash; Dan Stinebring</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >Jing was a ray of sunshine in all of our lives. He had the rare
              talent of being able to</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >bring any group of people together and brighten the mood in a
              room, just by the power of</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >his presence. His passion for sampling everything life has to
              offer was inspirational.
            </span>
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >At all times, he was just off from a fresh experience. Visiting a
              baseball game, making a trip</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >to Niagara Falls, buying an old video camera in a garage sale..
              There are too many to</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >count - he really lived his life to the fullest. Jing was
              unbelievably kind, always</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >offering his help and advice and never expecting anything in
              return. He was an incredible</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >storyteller and it was so nice to listen to his stories and
              opinions. It has been a</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >privilege knowing Jing and I am missing him greatly. It is a
              terrible, terrible loss for</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0">the world. &ndash; Pavel Motloch</span>
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >I did not know Jing well but I knew of him by his excellent
              scientific reputation. &nbsp;I heard his name over and over in
              meetings and conversations about pulsar timing. &nbsp;He was
              clearly a world class expert who was admired by so many people.
              &nbsp;He was a brilliant scientist who was highly respected by his
              peers. &nbsp;I am so sorry I will never have the chance to talk
              with him. &nbsp;It is a horrible loss and a terrible tragedy that
              he was taken so young, in his prime, with so much promise. &nbsp;I
              feel heartbroken for his family and friends. &ndash; VIctoria
              Kaspi</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >&ldquo;I met Jing at the IPTA meeting in Thailand in 2013. He was
              immediately likable and over the years I never saw him without a
              smile on his face. A great loss to the world. So very sad.&rdquo;
              - Paul Brook.</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >&ldquo;Jing was an absolutely unforgettable presence at CITA.
              I&rsquo;ll never forget how we used to joke about being
              hat-wearers in the building, and about how he roped me into a
              &lsquo;prank&rsquo; where we swapped out everyone&rsquo;s
              photographs for drawings. Jing was always very humble, yet funny,
              adding his own self-portrait to the board with his iconic hat. He
              gifted me with a Van Gogh magnet, with a hat, that I still have on
              my board at home, along with other treasures from friends. I wish
              I could tell him that I treasured that, and that he was a treasure
              in all aspects of his presence. Rest well, space cowboy.&rdquo; -
              Emily Tyhurst</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >So sad, so sad. &nbsp;A recurring memory is of Jing&rsquo;s
              beaming presence in the coffee room, especially at CITA desserts.
              &nbsp;Jing exuded a unique joie de vivre. &nbsp;Matching his
              majestic hat, Jing had an outsized ability to listen, care, and
              befriend. What a terrible loss, for his community of colleagues
              and friends, and the more so for his family. I will remember his
              great humanity. &nbsp;(Virtual) hugs to all in this time of
              grieving. &nbsp;- Peter Martin</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c11 c18"
              >I first met Jing when he came to the US for his Masters. He was a
              goofy kid and instantly made buddies with everyone around with his
              super friendly nature. He and I became very close friends, first
              as classmates and then as flatmates, and it was an absolute joy
              being around him. We were both wide eyed young lads in a foreign
              land and were there for each other on so many occasions, enjoying
              Lord of the Rings and Galaxy Quest on our super comfortable sofas,
              playing Borderlands on our PS4 after a long day at work, crying
              over breakups with girlfriends and problems at work, nerding over
              Elon Musk, sharing our dinners and our dreams. I learnt so much
              from him. He was a friend, a mentor, and an inspiration to me. I
              owe my sanity during PhD to his friendship. We kept meeting even
              after moving out of grad school, in China, in Germany. I cannot
              believe that he is not around. I will always miss him&hellip;
              &ndash; Sourabh
            </span>
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c11 c18"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c11 c18"
              >I am so shocked to hear this. Santiago was a very familiar face
              to the Forr&oacute; group, always willing to learn new moves and
              try them out. At our last class in December, he and I were joking
              around and I attempted to lead him in the dance and he tried
              following, despite him being a foot taller than me. One move
              involved the lead letting go of the follower, and the follow
              raising their hands above their head, and we attempted it, but we
              were messing up so bad and we had to stop dancing because we were
              laughing SO hard! You&#39;ll be greatly missed, Dr Santiago.
              &nbsp;- Sal</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >I remember when I started at CITA in late 2019, Jing was one of
              those people who you could immediately tell was adored by
              everyone. He was confident, competent and welcoming, and he seemed
              to bring a smile with him wherever he went. I&rsquo;m grateful to
              have gotten to know him and for those few welcome moments of
              normalcy over the last few years at CITA desserts, seminars and
              group lunches. Jing was someone whose presence was undeniable at
              CITA, you just knew he belonged, and he made you feel like you did
              too. It won&rsquo;t be quite the same without him. My condolences
              to his family and friends. - Nathan Carlson</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >Santiago, from the bottom of my heart.. It was a pleasure to have
              met you. You were one of the kindest people I had the honour of
              meeting. Every &nbsp;time I saw you, you were always smiling no
              matter what situation. Thank you for tolerating my spontaneous
              visits to your house and my mediocre dancing skills. Thank you for
              teaching me about the stars and the galaxies. Thank you for
              letting me be a part of your life. Your time here is done, but I
              know we will meet again soon, so till then&hellip; I&rsquo;ll be
              looking forward to being your dance partner again. - Jordan</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >&nbsp;I knew Jing through my roommate Jade. Quickly he became a
              vibrant part of our friend group and we enjoyed a lot of nice
              hangouts together. I remember the first time I met Jing, when we
              parted ways to go home I fell off my bike. Of course Jing then
              biked with me and my bleeding knee all the way home, even though
              it was in the opposite direction for him. Jing was always so kind
              and had a wonderful smile and energy that could make anyone feel
              happy. I wish he was still here. We are all so lucky to have known
              him. - Emily Lawrence</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >Jing Santiago started attending Forr&oacute; dance classes around
              4 years ago, in 2018. He was very eager to learn, sometimes he
              would joke that he was nervous dancing with me &quot;as one of the
              instructors&quot;. He loved to make people smile while dancing,
              always with a big smile and a compliment. He attended our special
              events (during our Saint John party with his cowboy hat and some
              mustaches he shared with others at the party) and workshops as
              much as his career and family visits allowed him. It was shocking
              to our community to learn this sad news. Last I saw Santiago was
              in December 2021, when we restarted in person classes. One class
              he brought 2 friends, who were very kind to inform us by e-mail
              about this sad news. We danced a lot and he forgot his backpack in
              class, then had to pick it up at my place the next day. He was
              always the light of the event, dancing or any other social
              activity after class. Santiago was full of life and kindness,
              always welcoming people and sharing his love for life. Our prays
              are with his family and friends - Maristela</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >I met Jing when I came to CITA for an internship over the summer.
              We went on a trip with our group to Algonquin to install a
              Christmas tree feed. He designed a logo and printed badges for us,
              like we were a squad on a special mission, it was really funny. (I
              still wear this badge proudly on my backpack!) One evening, a few
              of us went with him on a canoe and crossed the entire lake there
              and back. We could see the Milky Way so clearly, and the telescope
              dish in the distance. This was one night I will never forget. It
              happened because Jing suggested we go on the canoe. Another
              evening, after everybody went to sleep, he and I stayed awake and
              chatted for a long time. After that night, I felt like I met a new
              best friend. All of my best memories from that summer include him.
              He made me feel extremely welcome in an environment where I felt
              very alone and foreign. My stay in Toronto was brief, and I did
              not get to spend nearly as much time with him as I hoped. My
              condolences to his family and friends. - Daniela Breitman</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >At dance events in the forro community in Toronto, Jing/Santiago
              was always one of my favorite dance partners. He started each
              dance with a huge smile and warm greeting, and his lively spirit
              created a joyful atmosphere in every dance we shared - regardless
              of whether or not we got the dance moves correct. He was also very
              earnest in trying to learn difficult dance sequences - I remember
              trying to learn one with him in November 2021, and we had to stop
              dancing because we were laughing too much together. To me he felt
              like a true gentleman who treated each dance partner with care. I
              think his passing is all the more heartbreaking because he was not
              someone simply going through the motions of life - it felt like he
              tried to truly enjoy and make the most of each moment and
              relationship he had. I wish he could have had more time. I send
              heartfelt condolences to his family and friends. - Calla
              McLachlan</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >His unending positivity and intellectual humility are what I
              admire and will remember most about Santiago. Thank you to his
              family for raising a wonderful person; and to everyone around him
              who contributed to who he was. I am grateful that our paths were
              able to cross. - Jimmy Kizito</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >Vou contar uma hist&oacute;ria um milh&atilde;o de vezes</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >Sobre um cowboy, forr&oacute;zeiro, atronautico Chin&ecirc;s
              chamado Santiago.
            </span>
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >T&atilde;o inteligente, carinhoso, generoso e amig&aacute;vel.
            </span>
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >Eu vou sentir saudades de sempre de repente te-esbarrar, do seu
              jeito e nosso conversa&ccedil;&atilde;o, da tua hist&oacute;ria e
              teus adventuras.
            </span>
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >Sei que l&aacute; no c&eacute;u voc&ecirc; est&aacute;
              dan&ccedil;ando enquanto n&oacute;s estamos chorando. Mas
              agrade&ccedil;o por compartilhar o seu tempo e energia especial
              conosco.</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2"><span class="c0">&hellip;</span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >I find myself wondering how he became so wonderful, so special. I
              am endlessly grateful that our lives crossed paths, and even
              though I am so heartbroken, I feel grateful to have been his
              friend and so thankful he was born. I feel he is watching us from
              the stars, seeing the constellation of smiles, laughs and
              inspiration he left. I hope to live and love more like you did,
              Santiago. My deepest condolences to the family. - Vanessa Sabucco
            </span>
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >I remember Jing telling us at one of the many parties he hosted
              that when he was a child, he stared into the night sky and was
              afraid, which made him want to learn about the universe. I
              remember thinking how good a teacher he must be. A few months
              later, my partner&#39;s younger brother, Kuon, who was preparing
              to apply to university and was interested in astrophysics, wanted
              to learn more about the discipline. Jing agreed to have a
              conversation with him right away. I remember it was an evening, on
              a workday, and Jing was patient, genuinely interested in this shy
              teenager who had his camera turned off on Zoom. Jing told him
              about his career, shared anecdotes he knew would interest Kuon and
              eventually got this shy teenager to open up. Jing&#39;s outgoing
              personality and kindness extended to all his friend&#39;s friends.
              I got to know Jing through Jade and was invited to the subsequent
              gatherings held at his place after attending a barbeque. For
              Christmas (it was during COVID), I remember he invited a few of us
              stuck in Toronto, internationals away from our families, to have
              hotpot. It was cold, but we played games, laughed a lot, and
              shared stories. There is a polaroid photo of us from that night;
              we looked like a happy family. - Sheung-King Aaron Tang</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >Jing was one of the first people to make me feel truly welcome in
              NANOGrav. He had a special talent for seeking out newcomers and
              befriending them, and his joy and enthusiasm were infectious for
              everyone around him, even people he had just met. I distinctly
              remember the last time I saw him at a conference in Hawaii. He
              gave me the biggest hug, and was so delighted to catch up. I
              treasure that memory so much more now, knowing that I won&rsquo;t
              see him again. It&rsquo;s hard to imagine a world without Jing. He
              was truly one of a kind. &ndash; Stella Ocker</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >I cannot believe that Jing has been taken from us so soon. I am
              so, so sorry for what his family and close friends must be going
              through right now.</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >Jing was a really special person. I feel that he really embraced
              all of the experiences that life had to offer, whether it was
              travel, friendships, or his work, all of which he was clearly
              passionate about. I am thankful, for his sake and his
              family&rsquo;s, to know that he had a wonderful life and so many
              people who cared about him.</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >Jing was one of the first people who I met in the NANOGrav
              collaboration. It was in 2011 and I was at an IPTA student
              meeting, and I knew no one aside from one of the instructors. Jing
              came right up to me and started a conversation, and I was struck
              by how outgoing and friendly he was. We hung out at another
              conference a few years later; I remember he was wearing a cowboy
              hat, talking about how much he loved Texas and the U.S., joking
              about how he needed to find a cowgirl, and just having a really
              good time.</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >Because Jing was so passionate about his work, I just want to add
              that he made such important contributions to astrophysics. He
              wrote the PINT pulsar timing package, which is a huge achievement.
              And just in the last few weeks, he found the cause of a mysterious
              issue affecting some of the pulsars in a new gravitational-wave
              data set, which was crucial for being able to move forward with
              analysis.</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >I&rsquo;m really going to miss Jing as both a friend and a
              collaborator. I&rsquo;m so grateful to have gotten to know him and
              work with him over the years. &ndash; Megan DeCesar</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >Jing and I came from the same region and same college in China.
              We didn&#39;t know each other until a few months after I came to
              the US for the same graduate program. Looking back, he has been a
              big part of the path-finding years of my life. We traveled as
              friends, celebrated holidays like family, and went through
              milestones together.</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >His optimistic, carefree, welcoming characters, inherited from
              his family, had spanned so much fun, and shed so much light on my
              time in Texas. He is the type of person who drags the world to
              you, so long as you are curious and open to challenges.
            </span>
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >To name a few, he &lsquo;signed me up&rsquo; for the STEMs club,
              physics circles, living history, Renaissance, shooting ranch, road
              trips, bonfire on the beach, and tons of volunteering activities.
              Life has been quite monotonous since we parted after graduation.
            </span>
          </p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >We are so close to the end of the pandemic, that I cannot believe
              that we cannot have another adventure together. I&rsquo;d rather
              hope you were just having fun in a different place and forgot
              about me. I will really miss you, my friend. &nbsp;&mdash; Domi
              Jin</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >I first met Jing when we were both undergraduate visiting an
              Observatory. He quickly became friends with everyone and kept
              everyone in the loop even after the internship was over. He is so
              friendly, outgoing and always smiling. He is such a good friend.
              He always welcomes the new people. He always stops by to have a
              little chitchat with his old friends. He has many ideas to cheer
              people up. For all these years knowing him, I am amazed how he has
              always been so passionate about everything he loves. He loves
              history, so he joined the group of living history. He loves
              traveling and photography, so he took so many wonderful pictures
              of all the places he went &nbsp;and he loves sharing with people
              while telling the story behind.. He loves science, so he became a
              scientists! There are many more things he loves and enjoyed and
              the list can go on. So many memories pouring into mind, the times
              we laughed together, made fun of each other and stories behind the
              trips we had together. He wil be deeply missed. - Wenhui
            </span>
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c15">
            <span class="c0"
              >We were so honored to have Jin in our living history group. As a
              National Park Service volunteer, Jin created opportunities for
              visitors to connect to the stories of the U.S.-Mexican War. As a
              member of our crew, Jin brought joy and friendship that will be
              forever missed. Rest easy soldado. Daniel Ibarra, Chief of
              Interpretation &ndash; Palo Alto Battlefield National Historical
              Park</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c15">
            <span class="c0"
              >Jing was always happy to help others. He was brilliant, kind, and
              warm. I remember all the discussions with him about Chinese
              history when we had lunch and dinner together. It would have been
              nice to have chatted longer. He will be missed! &nbsp;
              &mdash;&mdash;Hongming Zhu</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2">
            <span class="c0"
              >Jing&#39;s family and loved ones must be experiencing
              overwhelming grief, for which I send my condolences. &nbsp;I
              always looked forward to my professional and social interactions
              with Jing because of his unceasingly cheerful spirit. &nbsp;Jing
              made important contributions to our academic community, both in
              the forms of tangible scientific advances, and by having added his
              distinct charm to the culture within our circles. &nbsp;His legacy
              will stay with us long after this untimely tragedy. &nbsp;I am so
              sorry that Jing is no longer here for you, for us. &nbsp;&ndash;
              Tim Pennucci</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c2 c5"><span class="c0"></span></p>
          <p class="c31">
            <span class="c1"
              >I met Jing Luo for the first time at the gravitational-wave
              summer school in Kunming in 2009. We met again in fall 2011, when
              I returned to UT-Brownsville (UTB, renamed UTRGV in 2015) as a
              postdoc, and he enrolled as a graduate student of UTB one year
              earlier. We were both doing research on pulsar timing arrays under
              the command of Frederick (Rick) Jenet, so I have more interactions
              with him than other Chinese students in Brownsville. We often went
              together to places near campus, such as Subway, McDonald&rsquo;s,
              Wing stop, etc., for lunch. Every Monday is our &ldquo;Big Mac
              day&rdquo;. Under Texas&rsquo;s big sky and scorching sun we
              walked to one of these eateries talking about various, if not all,
              kinds of topics on the road. I recall, perhaps, Jing started to
              get used to wearing a cowboy&rsquo;s hat since then. We
              participated in the annual meeting of the NANOGrav and IPTA each
              year. During the long journeys, we had been chatting about the
              obstacles in our research, anxiety before giving a talk,
              Rick&rsquo;s gossip, and, of course, Cixin Liu&rsquo;s
              &ldquo;Three bodies&rdquo;. Later, sometimes I poured out words
              about this quite popular science fiction with other friends, but
              in fact, I have never flipped any page of the three volumes.</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c17" id="h.gjdgxs">
            <span class="c1"
              >I don&rsquo;t remember exactly when, maybe at one of the IPTA
              meetings, Jing told me that he want to make a new and modern
              software package for pulsar timing, to upgrade the
              &ldquo;old&rdquo; Tempo2 built by George Hobbs et al. I suspect,
              since then, some of the big guys in this field, including George,
              would have somewhat &ldquo;disdained&rdquo; Jing&rsquo;s bold
              idea, which maybe mainly due to its name PINT (Pint Is Not
              Tempo3). What is valuable is Jing insisted and slowly making
              progresses so that some of the big guys in this field started to
              notice and even joined in the development of PINT. At the end of
              November 2014, when I was leaving Brownsville, it seems to me that
              PINT was still a baby and far from completeness. Surprisingly and
              happily, PINT has been gradually growing, iterating and maturing
              over the years. I believe Jing&rsquo;s persistence and diligence
              is an importance drive of theses progresses. When he was visiting
              China in the summer 2016, we invited him to give a talk on PINT at
              the Institute of Astrophysics in Huazhong University of Science
              and Technology. More recently, in January 2021, we invited him to
              give us an update on PINT online. After his talk, PINT gained
              several more users. As a researcher in this field, I can clearly
              see that PINT has already become self-contained and matured [Luo
              et al., ApJ 2021], actually it has already been applied in the
              data analysis of the NANOGrav 12.5-yr data release [Alam et al.,
              ApJS, 2021a,b]. I have received an automatic email from GitHub for
              PINT, that was a new fix made by Jing at 4:13 PM on February 15
              (local time of Toronto), perhaps, just a few hours before he
              passed away.</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c17">
            <span class="c1"
              >The other night, I had a dream about Jing: He had been in a deep
              sleep for three days without waking up. His families and friends
              were all surrounding him and very worried about him. At the last
              moment of the dream, Jing woke up and sat up, emerging on his face
              is his hallmark smile ...
            </span>
          </p>
          <p class="c17">
            <span class="c1"
              >It is impossible for me to really image the pain of Jing&rsquo;s
              parents at this moment. And there seems nothing I could do for
              them. Perhaps only time and the memories living in our hearts
              could bring them a glimpse of console.</span
            >
          </p>
          <p class="c17">
            <span class="c1">Goodbye, bro. We will miss you. </span>
          </p>
          <p class="c5 c17"><span class="c1"></span></p>
          <p class="c20"><span class="c1">Yan Wang</span></p>
          <p class="c20"><span class="c1">Feb. 23, 2022. Wuhan</span></p>
          <p class="c5 c30"><span class="c1"></span></p>
          <p class="c6 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p>
